{
  "What is the average salinity of ocean water?": "",
  "35 parts per thousand": "",
  "15 parts per thousand": "",
  "45 parts per thousand": "",
  "25 parts per thousand": "",
  "The average salinity of ocean water is approximately 35 parts per thousand (ppt), or about 3.5%. This means that for every kilogram of seawater, roughly 35 grams are dissolved salts.": "",
  "Which two ions make up the majority of dissolved salts in seawater?": "",
  "Calcium and magnesium": "",
  "Sodium and chloride": "",
  "Potassium and sulfate": "",
  "Bicarbonate and bromide": "",
  "Sodium (Na⁺) and chloride (Cl⁻) together account for about 85% of the dissolved salts in seawater. This is why ocean water tastes salty and why table salt (NaCl) is the dominant dissolved compound.": "",
  "What is the primary source of salts dissolved in ocean water?": "",
  "Decomposition of marine organisms": "",
  "Rain dissolving atmospheric gases": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions on the ocean floor only": "",
  "Chemical weathering of rocks on land": "",
  "The primary source of dissolved salts in the ocean is chemical weathering of rocks on land. Rivers carry dissolved minerals from weathered rocks into the ocean, where they accumulate over geological time.": "",
  "Which of the following is the most abundant dissolved gas in seawater?": "",
  "Carbon dioxide": "",
  "Nitrogen": "",
  "Argon": "",
  "Oxygen": "",
  "Nitrogen is the most abundant dissolved gas in seawater, just as it is the most abundant gas in the atmosphere. However, most marine organisms cannot use dissolved nitrogen directly; it must first be converted by nitrogen-fixing bacteria.": "",
  "What is the typical pH range of surface ocean water?": "",
  "9.0–9.5": "",
  "6.0–6.5": "",
  "7.8–8.3": "",
  "7.0–7.5": "",
  "Surface ocean water is slightly basic, with a typical pH range of about 7.8 to 8.3. This pH is maintained by the ocean's carbonate buffering system, which resists rapid changes in acidity.": "",
  "Which process adds chloride ions to the ocean?": "",
  "Evaporation of freshwater": "",
  "Absorption of atmospheric nitrogen": "",
  "Photosynthesis by marine plants": "",
  "Outgassing from volcanic activity": "",
  "Chloride ions are primarily added to the ocean through volcanic outgassing. Volcanoes release hydrogen chloride (HCl) gas, which dissolves in water and contributes chloride ions to the ocean over geologic time.": "",
  "What happens to the salinity of seawater when evaporation increases?": "",
  "Salinity stays the same": "",
  "Salinity fluctuates randomly": "",
  "Salinity decreases": "",
  "Salinity increases": "",
  "When evaporation increases, water molecules leave the ocean as vapor, but the dissolved salts remain behind. This concentrates the salts in a smaller volume of water, increasing the salinity.": "",
  "Which of the following is a major cation found in seawater?": "",
  "Sulfate": "",
  "Chloride": "",
  "Magnesium": "",
  "Bicarbonate": "",
  "Magnesium (Mg²⁺) is one of the major cations in seawater, ranking as the third most abundant ion after chloride and sodium. It plays important roles in marine chemistry and biology.": "",
  "Where is salinity typically highest in the open ocean?": "",
  "In deep ocean trenches based on": "",
  "At the poles, particularly regarding": "",
  "In the subtropical regions around 25°–30° latitude": "",
  "Near the equator according to": "",
  "Salinity is highest in the subtropical regions (~25°–30° latitude) because these areas experience high evaporation rates and relatively low precipitation. The equator, despite warm temperatures, receives heavy rainfall that dilutes surface salinity.": "",
  "What is the principle of constant proportions in seawater chemistry?": "",
  "The relative proportions of major ions remain nearly constant regardless of total salinity": "",
  "The amount of dissolved oxygen is always proportional to salinity": "",
  "The total amount of salt in the ocean never changes": "",
  "All oceans have exactly the same salinity": "",
  "The principle of constant proportions (Marcet's principle) states that while total salinity may vary, the ratios of major dissolved ions to each other remain remarkably constant throughout the world's oceans. This allows scientists to estimate total salinity by measuring just one ion.": "",
  "What does the term \"salinity\" refer to in marine science?": "",
  "The total concentration of dissolved salts in water": "",
  "The pressure at a given depth": "",
  "The temperature of seawater": "",
  "The amount of oxygen in water": "",
  "Salinity is defined as the total concentration of dissolved salts in water, typically measured in parts per thousand (ppt) or practical salinity units (PSU). It is one of the most important physical properties of seawater.": "",
  "What is a \"conservative element\" in ocean chemistry?": "",
  "An element whose proportion to total salinity remains constant": "",
  "An element whose concentration changes rapidly with depth": "",
  "An element found only in polar waters": "",
  "An element that is toxic to marine life": "",
  "A conservative element is one whose ratio to total salinity stays constant throughout the ocean. Sodium and chloride are examples. Their concentrations are not significantly affected by biological processes, so they mix uniformly.": "",
  "What does the term \"dissolved oxygen\" mean?": "",
  "Oxygen released during volcanic eruptions": "",
  "Oxygen that has been chemically bonded to hydrogen in water molecules": "",
  "Oxygen gas that is mixed into and held within water": "",
  "Oxygen stored in coral skeletons": "",
  "Dissolved oxygen refers to molecular oxygen (O₂) gas that is physically mixed into water rather than chemically bonded. Marine organisms rely on this dissolved oxygen for respiration, and its levels vary with temperature, salinity, and biological activity.": "",
  "What is a \"buffer\" in the context of ocean chemistry?": "",
  "A layer of warm water above cold water": "",
  "A physical barrier between ocean currents": "",
  "A type of marine sediment": "",
  "A substance that resists changes in pH when acids or bases are added": "",
  "In ocean chemistry, a buffer is a chemical system that resists changes in pH. The ocean's primary buffer is the carbonate system, involving dissolved CO₂, bicarbonate, and carbonate ions, which helps maintain relatively stable pH levels.": "",
  "What does \"residence time\" mean for a dissolved element in the ocean?": "",
  "The time it takes for the element to reach the deep ocean": "",
  "The average time an atom of that element stays in the ocean before being removed": "",
  "The time it takes for the element to dissolve": "",
  "The time between volcanic eruptions that add that element": "",
  "Residence time is the average time a dissolved element remains in the ocean before being removed by processes such as sedimentation, biological uptake, or chemical precipitation. Sodium has a very long residence time (~260 million years), while iron has a very short one.": "",
  "What is meant by \"parts per thousand\" (ppt) in measuring salinity?": "",
  "Grams of dissolved salt per kilogram of seawater": "",
  "The percentage of the ocean that is salt": "",
  "The number of ions per thousand liters": "",
  "The number of salt molecules per thousand water molecules": "",
  "Parts per thousand (ppt) expresses salinity as grams of dissolved salt per kilogram (1000 grams) of seawater. At 35 ppt, there are 35 grams of dissolved salts in every kilogram of seawater. The symbol ‰ is often used to represent ppt.": "",
  "What is a \"non-conservative element\" in ocean chemistry?": "",
  "An element found only in freshwater": "",
  "An element that does not dissolve in seawater": "",
  "An element whose concentration varies due to biological or chemical processes": "",
  "An element that is artificially introduced by humans": "",
  "A non-conservative element is one whose concentration in seawater is affected by biological uptake, chemical reactions, or other processes beyond simple mixing. Nutrients like nitrogen and phosphorus are non-conservative because organisms consume and release them.": "",
  "What does \"chemical weathering\" mean?": "",
  "The erosion of beaches by storms": "",
  "The physical breaking of rocks by wind and waves": "",
  "The rusting of human-made objects in the ocean": "",
  "The dissolving and chemical alteration of minerals by water and acids": "",
  "Chemical weathering is the breakdown of rocks through chemical reactions, often involving water, carbonic acid, or organic acids. This process dissolves minerals from rocks, releasing ions like sodium, calcium, and magnesium into rivers that carry them to the sea.": "",
  "What is a \"trace element\" in seawater?": "",
  "An element present in very small concentrations, often less than 1 ppm": "",
  "An element found only at the ocean surface": "",
  "An element introduced only by pollution": "",
  "An element that makes up more than 1% of seawater": "",
  "A trace element is one present in very small concentrations in seawater, typically less than 1 part per million (ppm). Examples include iron, zinc, and copper. Despite their low concentrations, trace elements can be essential for biological processes.": "",
  "What does the term \"halocline\" refer to?": "",
  "A zone of rapid salinity change with depth": "",
  "A zone where light cannot penetrate": "",
  "A zone of constant pressure in the deep ocean": "",
  "A zone of rapid temperature change with depth": "",
  "A halocline is a layer in the ocean where salinity changes rapidly with depth. It often occurs where freshwater from rivers or melting ice sits atop denser, saltier water. The halocline contributes to water column stratification.": "",
  "A marine biologist measures salinity at 28 ppt near the mouth of a large river. What is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "Deep ocean currents are bringing low-salinity water to the surface": "",
  "Freshwater discharge from the river is diluting the seawater": "",
  "Marine organisms are consuming the dissolved salts": "",
  "The ocean is losing salts through chemical reactions": "",
  "Near river mouths, freshwater mixes with seawater, creating a zone of reduced salinity called an estuary. The river's freshwater dilutes the dissolved salts, lowering measured salinity below the ocean average of ~35 ppt.": "",
  "A researcher finds that a sample of seawater from the Red Sea has a salinity of 40 ppt, well above average. Which factor best explains this?": "",
  "The Red Sea has very high evaporation and minimal freshwater input": "",
  "Volcanic activity in the Red Sea adds extra salt": "",
  "Cold temperatures cause salts to precipitate and then redissolve": "",
  "The Red Sea receives large volumes of river water": "",
  "The Red Sea is located in a hot, arid region with very high evaporation rates and almost no freshwater input from rivers or rainfall. As water evaporates, salts become more concentrated, leading to salinity above the global average.": "",
  "A student heats a 500 mL sample of seawater until all the water evaporates. Approximately how many grams of salt would remain?": "",
  "35 grams": "",
  "3.5 grams": "",
  "10 grams": "",
  "17.5 grams": "",
  "At 35 ppt salinity, there are 35 grams of salt per 1000 mL (1 kg) of seawater. For 500 mL, approximately half that amount (17.5 g) would remain after all the water evaporated. This calculation assumes a seawater density close to 1 g/mL.": "",
  "An oceanographer notices that chloride and sodium ratios are the same in water samples from the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans. Which concept does this demonstrate?": "",
  "The principle of constant proportions": "",
  "Biological magnification": "",
  "Ocean acidification": "",
  "Thermohaline circulation": "",
  "This demonstrates the principle of constant proportions, which states that the ratios of major dissolved ions in seawater are nearly the same everywhere in the ocean. Regardless of total salinity, sodium and chloride maintain a consistent ratio.": "",
  "During a drought, a coastal lagoon becomes isolated from the ocean. Over time, what would you expect to happen to its salinity?": "",
  "Salinity would drop to zero without ocean input": "",
  "Salinity would remain the same since it is saltwater": "",
  "Salinity would decrease as organisms consume salt": "",
  "Salinity would increase due to continued evaporation without replenishment": "",
  "An isolated lagoon during a drought would experience ongoing evaporation without freshwater or ocean water replenishment. As water evaporates, dissolved salts become more concentrated, steadily raising salinity—potentially beyond normal ocean levels.": "",
  "A desalination plant removes dissolved salts from seawater to produce drinking water. Which ions would the plant remove in the greatest quantities?": "",
  "Iron and manganese": "",
  "Gold and silver": "",
  "Nitrogen and phosphorus": "",
  "Since sodium and chloride make up about 85% of the dissolved salts in seawater, a desalination plant would remove these two ions in the greatest quantities. Other ions like magnesium and sulfate would also be removed, but in smaller amounts.": "",
  "A scientist measures the salinity at the ocean surface near the equator and finds it lower than at 25° N latitude. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "More rivers flow into the ocean at 25° N": "",
  "Heavy equatorial rainfall dilutes the surface salinity": "",
  "Marine organisms at the equator consume more salt": "",
  "The equator is colder so less salt dissolves": "",
  "The equatorial region receives heavy rainfall from the Intertropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ), which dilutes surface salinity. The subtropical region at 25° N has less precipitation and high evaporation, resulting in higher salinity.": "",
  "A student notices that iron has a residence time of only about 200 years, while sodium has a residence time of ~260 million years. What can be inferred?": "",
  "Iron is added to the ocean much faster than sodium": "",
  "There is much more iron than sodium in the ocean": "",
  "Sodium is more chemically reactive in seawater than iron": "",
  "Iron is removed from seawater by chemical and biological processes much faster than sodium": "",
  "A short residence time means an element is removed from the ocean quickly relative to its input. Iron is rapidly scavenged by biological uptake and chemical precipitation, while sodium is highly soluble and not readily removed, giving it an extremely long residence time.": "",
  "In the Arctic, sea ice is forming during winter. How does this process affect the salinity of the surrounding water?": "",
  "Salinity remains unchanged during freezing": "",
  "Salinity of the surrounding water increases because salts are excluded during freezing": "",
  "Salinity decreases because freezing removes salt": "",
  "Salinity increases in the ice but decreases in the water": "",
  "When seawater freezes, the ice crystal structure excludes most dissolved salts, which are expelled into the surrounding liquid water. This brine rejection increases the salinity and density of the water beneath the ice, which can drive deep ocean circulation.": "",
  "A coastal city is considering using seawater for agricultural irrigation. Based on your knowledge of seawater chemistry, what is the main concern?": "",
  "The high dissolved salt concentration would damage soil and harm most crops": "",
  "Seawater contains too many dissolved gases": "",
  "Seawater lacks the nutrients plants need": "",
  "Seawater is too acidic for plant roots": "",
  "At ~35 ppt salinity, seawater contains far too much dissolved salt for most crops. The high sodium and chloride concentrations would cause osmotic stress in plants, preventing water uptake, and would lead to salt accumulation in the soil over time.": ""
}